This paper focuses on the performance evaluation and optimization of a permissioned blockchain platform, Hyperledger Fabric. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) category. Additionally, the paper discusses potential security vulnerabilities and performance bottlenecks, which could also place it in the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) category. The study also involves the use of a state database, which could make it relevant to the Database (cs.DB) category. The paper also discusses the optimization of the platform, which could place it in the Software Engineering (cs.SE) category. Finally, the paper involves the use of smart contracts, which could make it relevant to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) category.
